===Etymology===
Recorded since 1538, either (for its original color) from Medieval (=modern) French ''[[#French|carnation]]'' "person's color or complexion" (probably from {{etyl|it}} [[carnagione]] "flesh color," from Late {{etyl|la}} [[carnatio]] "fleshiness", from Latin [[caro]] "flesh") or a corruption of [[coronation]] (from [[coronare]] 'to crown', from [[corona]] 'crown'; because of the flower's use in chaplets or from the toothed crown-like look of the petals).

